Public vs Private;  static vs non-static;  const

Public member functions:
a) 	Static int function() 	vs. 	int function()

A static int function belongs to the class itself, not any specific instance. 
It can be called without creating an instance of the class. 

An int function belongs to a specific instance of the class and operates on that instance's data.

b) 	void function() 	vs. 	void function() const:

void function() can modify member variables of the class. 
void function() const cannot modify any member variables (except those marked as mutable).

Private member variables:
a) 	Static int 	vs. 	int:

A static int variable is shared among all instances of the class. 
An int variable is unique to each instance of the class.

b) 	Getting and setting values:
Yes, you typically need member functions (getters and setters) to access and modify static int and int variables, 
especially if they are private.

c) 	Const member functions:

You would use int function() const if the function needs to access member variables without modifying them. 
This ensures the function doesn't change the object's state.

d)	Calling the static member function
int numAccounts = Account::getNbAccounts();

e)	Calling the non-static member function on an instance
Account a(100);
int amount = a.checkAmount();
